    <name>
				<text>19.1.4.3 Find general and specific solution</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Find the family of solutions of the differential equation</p>
\[\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} = {@exp@}.\]
<p>Make sure to include the arbitrary constant in your solution.</p>
<p>\(y = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>
<p>Now find the unique solution such that \(y({@x1@}) = {@y1@}\).</p>
<p>\(y = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>We are asked for the general solution of the differential equation</p>
\[\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} = {@exp@}.\]
<p>We begin by integrating the equation with respect to \(x\). This gives the family of solutions:</p>
\[y = \int {@exp@} \,\mathrm{d}x = {@ta1@}\]
<p>Next, we are asked to find the unique solution such that \(y({@x1@}) = {@y1@}\). In order
    to do this, we must find the corresponding value of \(c\).
</p>
\[y({@x1@}) = {@y1@} \implies {@ev(ta1, x=x1)@} = {@y1@} \implies c = {@c1@}\]
<p>Therefore, the particular solution we seek is:</p>
\[y = {@ta2@}\]]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
